==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|credo|lang=ang}}, {{term|crede|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|creda|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|credo|lang=la||I believe}}, from {{term|credere||to believe|lang=la}}; akin to Old Irish {{term|cretim|lang=sga||I believe}}, and Sanskrit {{term|रद्दध्मि|tr=raddadhmi|lang=sa}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈkɹiːd/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|iːd|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia|dab=creed (disambiguation)|mul=Creed}}
{{en-noun}}

# That which is [[believe]]d; accepted [[doctrine]], especially [[religious]]; a particular set of [[belief]]s; any [[summary]] of [[principle]]s or [[opinion]]s [[profess]]ed or [[adhere]]d to.
# A [[reading]] or [[statement]] of belief that [[summarize]]s the [[faith]] it represents; a definite summary of what is believed; a [[confession]] of faith for public use; especially, one which is brief and comprehensive.
#* ''A '''creed''' is a [[manifesto]] of religious or spiritual beliefs''
# {{context|rare|lang=en}} The fact of [[believe|believing]]; [[belief]], [[faith]].
#* '''1819''', Lord Byron, ''Don Juan'', I:
#*: The precipice she stood on was immense, / So was her '''creed''' in her own innocence.

